The CodeIgniter &quot;[Static Pages][1]&quot; tutorial shows one possible way to do what you want.

In short, it demonstrates a `view` function that takes an argument. The argument is used to &quot;select&quot; the correct view.

The no-frills version might look like this.

    class Home extends CI_Controller
    {    
        public function view($page = &#39;home&#39;)
        {
            $this-&gt;load-&gt;view(&#39;pages/&#39;.$page);
        }
    }

The doc tutorial shows some other code you should consider adding.

To use the above, the link to Tickidology would be `https://example.com/home/view/tickidology` making the value of `$page` equal to `&#39;tickidology&#39;`. You can use routing to eliminate the need to include &#39;view/&#39; in the URI if you like.

The default value of `$page` is &#39;home&#39; which may or may not be relevant to your site. The idea is that if `Home::view()` is called without an argument there is still a (default) view to be loaded.

While not part of the answer, I suggest you use the URL Helper function `anchor()` ([doc here][2]) to create your links, e.g.

    echo anchor(&#39;home/view/tikidology&#39;, &#39;Tickidology&#39;);

BTW, when using `base_url()` the URI segments can (should be) used as an argument to the function, e.g.

    &lt;href = &#39;&lt;?php echo base_url(&#39;home/view/tikidology&#39;); ?&gt;&#39;&gt;Tikidology&lt;/a&gt;

  [1]: https://codeigniter.com/user_guide/tutorial/static_pages.html
  [2]: https://codeigniter.com/user_guide/helpers/url_helper.html#anchor

